{
  "texts": [
    "The condition for being isomorphic as projective representations is often called as projective equivalence which in addition to basis changes allows the modification of the action of H L L ′ by a function (not necessarily a homomorphism) θ:H L L ′ → ×.For example, non-isomorphic one-dimensional linear representations of H L L ′ are all isomorphic to the trivial linear representation, when viewed as projective representations.Similarly, we can also consider some other lines in the two multiplets M L and M L ′.",
    "Nongenuine local operators changingL [g] ∈ M L to L [g ′] ∈ M L ′ form twisted representations of H L [g] L ′ [g ′]:= H L [g] ∩ H L ′ [g ′] ⊆ G (0).In fact, mathematically, all these twisted representations combine together to form a 1morphism in the 2-category 2-Rep(G (0)) formed by 2-representations of the group G (0).",
    "Such 1-morphisms are also referred to as intertwiners between the two 2-representations.",
    "Indeed, in our physical setup the non-genuine local operators lying between lines L, L ′ explicitly intertwine the action of 0-form symmetry G (0) on the two line operators.",
    "Thus, we have justified the p = q = 1 version of statement 1.5."
  ]
}